videoSnippet.title: Nihal Sarin Beats an International Master in 13 Moves!
videoSnippet.description:
#agadmator Nihal Sarin vs Einar Hjalti Jensson
Runavik Open 2017
Round 5
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 Be7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 O-O 7. Ngf3 b6 8. Ne5 Bb7 9. Qf3 Nbd7 10. Rd1 Rc8 11. Qh3 Re8 12. Ndf3 g6 13. Nxf7


Nihal was the 2014 World Under-10 Champion, winning the title ahead of several talented peers in Durban, South Africa.[3] In 2015, he came close to winning the Under-12 championship in Porto Carras, Greece but had to settle for silver on the tiebreak.[4] In the 2016 edition in Batumi, Georgia, Nihal tied for the second place, settling for the fourth position on the tiebreak.[5]

Nihal is a noted speed-chess specialist and is a key member of Team Delhi Dynamite in the inaugural edition of Chess.com's PRO Chess League 2017.
